\f1\b\fs32 Absolute pressure
\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f2\fs32  is a pressure measurement on a scale that increases from zero, where zero corresponds to the vacuum of space. Absolute pressure is always higher than the corresponding gage pressure by the amount of the atmospheric pressure. For shipboard purposes, you can simply add 14.7 psi to the gage reading in psi to get the absolute pressure. For example, a gage pressure of 100 psig would be the same as an absolute pressure of 114.7 psia. \
\pard\sb240\partightenfactor0
